09:50.042 --> 09:51.204
Do you empathize with that?

09:52.085 --> 09:53.607
Does it bemuse you in any way?

09:53.948 --> 09:57.453
No, I think... Do you share that passion?

09:58.014 --> 10:02.961
Well, you can help but get wrapped up in a little bit, but we see it often enough when people walk in this place.

10:03.278 --> 10:09.526
They're overwhelmed frequently, because these books are available for sale, and they're really surprised at that.

10:09.566 --> 10:15.534
We see it often enough that it's hard to get the same level of enthusiasm, you know?

10:16.155 --> 10:18.518
And so it's sort of like watching the birth process.

10:18.578 --> 10:20.721
The first time I saw it was, I believe, with the second time.

10:21.142 --> 10:23.966
You know, if you had 36 children, say, oh, my baby, you know?

10:24.106 --> 10:25.648
Yeah, you'd send it in if you had one of the kids.

10:26.349 --> 10:27.550
Right.

10:27.570 --> 10:32.577
So although we share some of the enthusiasm, and we recognize that it's

10:33.029 --> 10:40.696
You couldn't be a bibliomaniac, personally.

10:40.756 --> 10:42.197
You don't see it in your fabric.

10:42.257 --> 10:46.361
I think that I have to have a touch of it in me to have what I have.

10:46.941 --> 10:47.462
I really do.

10:47.522 --> 10:50.344
I think it's beyond coincidence that I'm in the book business.

10:50.744 --> 10:54.768
I'll give you this thing, by the way, I wrote called My First Year in the Business.

10:54.788 --> 10:55.368
I'd like that.

10:55.749 --> 10:59.452
It's just a three- or four-page article on how I got into the book business.

10:59.472 --> 11:02.935
I think that would be very useful.

11:03.438 --> 11:05.782
It's really mostly about Compton in my first year.

11:05.802 --> 11:09.006
It's more humorous than anything else, but it's truthful, as I recall.

11:09.047 --> 11:11.951
It's a very important thing.

11:12.312 --> 11:15.737
I expect that I'll call you at some point, too, to go over some things.

11:15.757 --> 11:17.499
You say, what does everything you say mean?

11:20.123 --> 11:23.809
You know, the beauty of these interviews is everyone is

11:24.025 --> 11:27.828
been different, and I've always come away with something I didn't expect.

11:28.989 --> 11:31.952
Well, I'm much more frivolous than most people.

11:31.992 --> 11:39.299
I mean, I really love what I do, but I don't take this business as seriously as most people in this business do.

11:39.319 --> 11:48.447
I mean, it's really fortuitous to be in a business where all your customers are basically pretty happy, financially well-off people.

11:48.647 --> 11:50.409
I mean, with fair exceptions, of course.

11:50.689 --> 11:51.990
The average guy who comes in this store,

11:52.223 --> 11:54.186
He's prepared to buy something fairly expensive.

11:54.266 --> 11:56.429
So chances are he's been fairly successful in life.

11:56.849 --> 11:57.951
He's indulging himself.

11:57.991 --> 11:59.613
Nobody needs what I have to sell.

12:00.274 --> 12:01.015
Who needs rare books?

12:01.656 --> 12:03.638
I mean, I have to create that interest, right?

12:04.239 --> 12:04.740
Do you think so?

12:05.100 --> 12:07.844
I don't, because nobody really, I don't think, nobody needs it.

12:07.864 --> 12:08.945
Nobody has to create that interest to me.

12:08.985 --> 12:09.446
I don't know.

12:09.606 --> 12:10.908
I want, my interest is here.

12:10.928 --> 12:11.509
Oh, I know.

12:11.529 --> 12:13.732
You just have to point the things out to me.

12:13.832 --> 12:17.016
I know, but I'm talking about life's essentials.

12:17.317 --> 12:19.680
I mean, really, what is the priority?

12:20.321 --> 12:22.705
Sometimes it's really confusing to most books.

12:22.745 --> 12:30.616
If you ask any bookseller in the most honest moment, you know, does he really totally believe that this book is worth $50,000?

12:30.636 --> 12:35.764
I mean, $50,000 is the purchasing power of it versus other things in this world.

12:35.804 --> 12:37.547
It's really confusing sometimes.

12:37.647 --> 12:40.351
What's your answer to that question?

12:40.691 --> 12:42.794
Oh, I think it's absolutely a personal decision.

12:43.055 --> 12:44.016
I mean, I just...

12:44.418 --> 12:49.184
Whenever I tell a person, don't be silly, don't buy it, I almost always sell it, right?

12:49.204 --> 12:52.168
If I say, oh, you have to have this book, you can't live without it, I don't believe that.

12:52.209 --> 12:53.650
I think you can live without everything.

12:53.671 --> 12:56.214
Although, I'll tell you one thing that Jake Zayton told me you could put this down.

12:58.797 --> 13:01.401
One day I had a client who was looking at a book for $3,000.

13:01.601 --> 13:02.543
He was thinking about it.

13:02.923 --> 13:04.125
He said, well, I don't know.

13:04.405 --> 13:06.568
And I said, well, I don't know.

13:06.708 --> 13:07.770
And he said, yeah, I'll take it.

13:07.970 --> 13:08.330
I'll take it.

13:08.390 --> 13:09.332
And I said, great.

13:09.352 --> 13:10.714
And I said, you know, I'm surprised you're buying it.

13:10.734 --> 13:11.675
It doesn't fit in your collection.

13:11.695 --> 13:13.277
And he said, you know,

13:13.443 --> 13:14.205
You're right, it doesn't.

13:14.366 --> 13:15.068
Maybe I won't take it.

13:15.148 --> 13:15.569
Put it back.

13:15.990 --> 13:23.993
And then I told Jake, because I had lunch with him that day, and he said, you know, he says, the one thing you should learn in this business, when a customer says, I'll take it, you stop talking.

13:24.074 --> 13:26.117
And it was pretty simple.

13:26.457 --> 13:26.998
I said, you're right.

13:27.018 --> 13:28.179
You know, and I made it.

13:28.199 --> 13:30.142
I got home and said, I can't believe it.

13:30.162 --> 13:33.086
I probably still have the book in my safe if you want to see it.

13:33.106 --> 13:33.587
I don't remember.

13:33.607 --> 13:34.648
But the point is, it's true.

13:34.928 --> 13:36.270
When a customer says, you know, I'll take it.

13:36.290 --> 13:38.233
There's a time, there's a time to shut up.

13:38.293 --> 13:38.673
Yeah, right.

13:38.934 --> 13:40.476
If anything, I get a little too chatty.

13:40.496 --> 13:42.038
And that time, I've since learned.

13:42.078 --> 13:43.299
I've never done that since.

13:43.319 --> 13:44.481
Because it's a personal decision.

13:44.761 --> 13:46.303
Why should I question what he should have?

13:46.363 --> 13:49.427
Well, how about if the guy says, $3,000 is too much, I give you $2,500.

13:50.429 --> 13:51.831
We do not do that.

13:51.871 --> 13:53.693
I mean, I occasionally, uh, I,

13:54.297 --> 14:03.830
I think every bookseller occasionally will be flexible in the price, you know, unless it's something he just acquired or he has other people for.

14:04.812 --> 14:08.697
