17:50.044 --> 17:51.386
You're president.

17:51.827 --> 17:52.968
Past president, right.

17:53.909 --> 18:00.557
Of the 400 members, over 200 members grossed less than $100,000 a year.

18:02.528 --> 18:07.558
And so, of the 400 members, I think there were less than 20 that grossed a million.

18:08.680 --> 18:09.762
That's how small the business was.

18:09.782 --> 18:12.768
So really, the Iraq figures to indicate that you're at the top of the field.

18:12.948 --> 18:15.974
I wasn't familiar with the census.

18:16.154 --> 18:16.515
Yeah.

18:16.535 --> 18:19.741
Well, I'm telling you, it'sâ€” Who's close to you?

18:19.761 --> 18:24.570
Well, probably the biggest grossing books, I assume, is Krauss in this country.

18:24.685 --> 18:26.407
Or you could say Strand.

18:26.528 --> 18:27.088
Or Argosy.

18:27.128 --> 18:28.951
I don't know what Argosy does.

18:28.971 --> 18:30.433
Well, yeah, but I'm talking about rare books.

18:30.453 --> 18:31.975
Those are volume used books.

18:31.995 --> 18:34.979
Yeah, because Strand, you know, Strand is a unique creature.

18:36.642 --> 18:37.403
Review books.

18:37.583 --> 18:44.392
But I don't, you know, it's never really been something I've thought of a great deal about.

18:44.412 --> 18:51.002
But I show you one thing, that in the future, if we don't, we're going to do something very dramatic in this business.

18:51.663 --> 18:52.684
I mean, very dramatic, like...

18:53.660 --> 19:00.287
What we're going to, if we don't expand dramatically or really build, we're going to have a large impact, you know, on the market in the future.

19:00.527 --> 19:01.508
I'm working on some things now.

19:01.528 --> 19:02.249
You've been new as a group?

19:02.269 --> 19:03.450
Are you an individual?

19:03.470 --> 19:12.660
Well, I've been, we've been actually, and I'd prefer if you didn't publish this, we've been offered to buy our company, I buy a very large company with a disc shop.

19:13.041 --> 19:19.988
We've been approached to buy us out there early in the year, and a lot of people in the business know about it, I don't know if you've heard it, buy a large company with a

19:20.407 --> 19:25.554
enormous portfolio who want to make a very serious purchase in their books and want the best to spearhead it.

19:25.574 --> 19:33.506
And we have negotiated for several months to buy me out and open a shop in New York and London, and that's why I said there's a possibility.

19:33.666 --> 19:36.971
My book is not coming out for another year and a half.

19:37.111 --> 19:38.773
It will be done or not done by that.

19:38.793 --> 19:40.195
This should all be resolved.

19:40.376 --> 19:42.439
It will be resolved in 90 days.

19:42.979 --> 19:45.503
Well, then I think I'd like to call it back in 90 days.

19:45.523 --> 19:48.287
Well, I mean, I know, I know, we've been

19:48.537 --> 19:51.101
I have contracts sitting in my box for two months, but I haven't.

19:51.121 --> 19:55.427
But these people want, in other words, there's a real possibility you might be out of this business.

19:55.447 --> 19:56.489
No, I wouldn't be out of it all.

19:56.529 --> 19:58.812
I'll be in charge of a very large organization.

19:58.832 --> 20:00.775
I mean, a large business.

20:00.795 --> 20:01.736
You'll have a parent.

20:01.756 --> 20:04.540
I'll have the largest bookshop in the world if this goes through.

20:04.560 --> 20:06.523
I mean, I could have it now if I wanted.

20:06.543 --> 20:16.097
The problem is if I sell out my business, I'm not a sub-Chapter S corporation, which means that if I sell out my business, say for every million dollars I get,

20:16.313 --> 20:22.682
My corporation pays 35 percent tax, and then the money left over goes to me, and I pay 35 percent of that, 40 percent of that.

20:22.722 --> 20:24.604
So I only end up with 30 percent on the dollar.

20:24.985 --> 20:26.647
So it's, right now, it's very unappealing.

20:27.088 --> 20:27.668
Yeah, exactly.

20:27.689 --> 20:31.113
No, but the opportunity they're offering me is what's exciting.

20:31.173 --> 20:32.856
Is this a non-book company?

20:32.896 --> 20:33.456
Nothing new with books.

20:33.476 --> 20:35.119
It's a company that's very cash-heavy.

20:35.579 --> 20:38.023
American or offshore, as they say?

20:38.043 --> 20:39.364
It's an American company.

20:40.386 --> 20:41.788
California-based or New York-based?

20:41.808 --> 20:44.211
Well, they have offices in seven countries.

20:44.613 --> 20:47.417
But there are principal offices in Los Angeles.

20:47.437 --> 20:54.386
But if these people say, hey, there's nobody serious in this business.

20:54.726 --> 20:55.988
There's no serious money in this business.

20:56.008 --> 20:57.109
There's no serious promotion.

20:57.990 --> 20:59.052
What do they see, though?

20:59.212 --> 21:01.235
Do they see a growth industry here?

21:02.857 --> 21:04.299
Well, let's put it this way.

21:04.339 --> 21:05.700
It's a diversification for them.

21:05.740 --> 21:06.942
It would probably, if they put out

21:07.175 --> 21:10.760
$20 million that would represent probably less than 1% of their assets.

21:11.060 --> 21:13.063
So it's just another thing for them.

21:13.083 --> 21:15.326
They're just looking for places to do this.

21:15.667 --> 21:18.411
And I think there's a glamour in the business that they find.

21:18.431 --> 21:19.032
They've been in.

21:19.392 --> 21:20.914
We've spoken to them.

21:20.954 --> 21:22.597
I flew to New York and London with them.

21:22.637 --> 21:24.680
I mean, we've went through this whole thing.

21:24.940 --> 21:26.122
So the talks are ongoing?

21:26.542 --> 21:27.684
The talks have been ongoing.

21:27.724 --> 21:31.870
